### Spring Boot MongoDB API Test Requests
### Base URL: http://localhost:8080
### All endpoints except /login require JWT authentication

### 1. Authentication - Get JWT Token
POST http://localhost:8080/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "Marcos",
  "password": "password"
}

### 2. Get All Users (requires JWT token)
### Extract token from login response body and use it here
### Example response from login: {"token":"eyJhbGciOiJIUzUxMiJ9...","type":"Bearer","expiresIn":864000000}
GET http://localhost:8080/api/user/
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN

### 3. Get User by ID (requires JWT token)
### Replace {user-id} and YOUR_JWT_TOKEN with actual values
GET http://localhost:8080/api/user/{{user-id}}
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN

### 4. Create New User (requires JWT token)
POST http://localhost:8080/api/user/
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN

{
  "name": "John Doe",
  "age": 30,
  "salary": 50000.0,
  "password": "newpassword123"
}

### 5. Update User (requires JWT token)
### Replace {user-id} and YOUR_JWT_TOKEN with actual values
PUT http://localhost:8080/api/user/{{user-id}}
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN

{
  "name": "John Updated",
  "age": 31,
  "salary": 55000.0,
  "password": "updatedpassword123"
}

### 6. Delete User (requires JWT token)
### Replace {user-id} and YOUR_JWT_TOKEN with actual values
DELETE http://localhost:8080/api/user/{{user-id}}
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN

### 7. Error Handling Examples

#### Invalid Credentials
POST http://localhost:8080/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "invalid",
  "password": "wrong"
}

#### Missing Token (should return 401 Unauthorized)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/user/

#### Invalid Token (should return 401 Unauthorized)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/user/
Authorization: Bearer invalid-token

#### User Not Found (should return 404 Not Found)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/user/507f1f77bcf86cd799439011
Authorization: Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN

### 8. Complete Test Workflow Variables
### Define variables for easier testing (supported by some HTTP clients)
@baseUrl = http://localhost:8080
@token = Bearer YOUR_JWT_TOKEN
@userId = {{user-id}}

### 9. Variable-based Requests (alternative format)

### Login with variables
POST {{baseUrl}}/login
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "username": "Marcos",
  "password": "password"
}

### Get all users with variables
GET {{baseUrl}}/api/user/
Authorization: {{token}}

### Create user with variables
POST {{baseUrl}}/api/user/
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: {{token}}

{
  "name": "Alice Smith",
  "age": 28,
  "salary": 45000.0,
  "password": "alicepass123"
}

### Update user with variables
PUT {{baseUrl}}/api/user/{{userId}}
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: {{token}}

{
  "name": "Alice Updated",
  "age": 29,
  "salary": 47000.0,
  "password": "alicepass456"
}

### Delete user with variables
DELETE {{baseUrl}}/api/user/{{userId}}
Authorization: {{token}}

### Notes:
### 1. Login returns JSON: {"token":"eyJhbGciOiJIUzUxMiJ9...","type":"Bearer","expiresIn":864000000}
### 2. Extract the token value and use it as: Authorization: Bearer <token>
### 3. Replace {user-id} with actual user ID from create/get responses
### 4. Some HTTP clients support variables (like @baseUrl) for easier testing
### 5. The application creates sample users "Marcos" and "Gerardo" automatically
### 6. JWT tokens are valid for 10 days by default
